  <slide>
    <title>Third Step: Use ARIA to improve the accessibility of Forms and Links</title>
    <contents>
      <ul>
        <li>Use <code>aria-required='true'</code> attribute on controls that are required</li>
        <li>Use <code>aria-invalid='true'</code> attribute on controls with invalid content or formatting,
          and use <code>aria-describedby</code> to point to a message on the problem and how to fix it</li>
        <li>When the HTML <code>label</code> element is insufficent for for labeling controls, use <code>aria-labelledby</code> and <code>aria-label</code> to label controls</li>
        <li>Use <code>aria-describedby</code> to provide context to links with the same or similar link text</li>
        <li>Use HTML5 <code>required</code> attribute instead of <code>aria-required</code> if you are supporting on HTML5 browers</li>
      </ul>
    </contents>
